{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499902"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1580"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1580"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.32,0.12,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46486"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1580"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31396"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"2362"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42345"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46486"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old man presents with painful discoloration of fingers in both hands. He also complains of itching over the affected skin. His medical history is unremarkable. He does not smoke or drink. It is winter and he has been doing a lot of work outside in the garden and believes that the cold exposure is causing the pain and itching in his fingers. His hand has the following appearance (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Advise to wear gloves","Topical corticosteroids","Calcium channel blockers","Phosphodiesterase inhibitors","Prostaglandins"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lesions are characteristic for chilblains\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eor pernio, which commonly affect the toes and fingers. It is worsened by cold conditions and may occur more frequently in the elderly. Secondary pernio may be associated with an underlying disease such as systemic lupus erythematosus (chilblain lupus).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most important initial management is to remove or avoid the cold insult. The patient should be advised to keep the affected areas warm and dry, using socks and gloves as \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarm protective wear\u003C/strong\u003E. Additionally, lifestyle\u00a0modifications including smoking cessation are recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing initial management, second line treatment can be considered. This includes \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium channel blockers\u003C/strong\u003E. Excessive and prolonged use of topical corticosteroids should be avoided as they may increase the likelihood of tissue atrophy. Calcium channel blockers have a vasodilatory effect - some small studies showed efficacy in reversing and preventing development of pernio lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphodiesterase inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostaglandins\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in the treatment of pernio. They are used in the treatment of resistant Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon (RP) which is a differential for this condition. Classical presentation of RP is that of a sudden onset of cold digits associated with a demarcation of skin pallor or cyanosis. After rewarming, there is vascular reperfusion, resulting in an erythema secondary to rebound of blood flow. Secondary Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon maybe associated with an underlying autoimmune disease. Management options include avoidance of cold insult, calcium channel blockers, topical nitrates. In resistant cases, phosphodiesterase inhibitors or prostaglandins may be given.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Avoidance of cold exposure is an important part of the management of chilblains.","Possible pharmacological treatment options for chilblains include the use of topical corticosteroids and calcium channel blockers, such as nifedipine."],"references":["Whitman PA, Crane JS. Pernio. [Updated 2021 Aug 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549842/","Imboden JB, Hellmann DB, Stone JA. Current diagnosis \u0026 treatment in rheumatology. McGraw Hill Professional; 2020 Oct 22"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31396"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1580"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19765"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19765"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ddf04332-d639-44b2-8d78-2262d9dad8a8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ddf04332-d639-44b2-8d78-2262d9dad8a8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":478}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31396"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-04T23:01:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-04T23:01:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1580"}},"content":{"data"